{"questionId":"19783","questionHtml":"<p>Explain why your line should not be used to estimate the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> at which&nbsp;the temperature is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>°</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Because the line should only be used to estimate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> and not <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math>. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>R1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[1 mark]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19783","referenceCode":"EXN.1.SL.TZ0.8c.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Explain why your line should not be used to estimate the value of m at which the temperature is 10.0 °C.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}